x4freetext: Copper foils (~30 mg/cm2) were sandwiched between pure
isolated and purified by relatively standard
purified elements were measured with thin-window beta
proportional counters. The results of the
computational treatment of the radioactivity data
were converted to relative production rates of the
nuclides under standard conditions by correcting for
losses during the chemical purifications, for the
efficiencies of detection of the radiations, and for
the growth and decay during and after the
irradiations. Monitoring of these irradiations was
achieved by "sandwiching" the copper foils between
pure aluminum foils, and using the production of 22Na
in the aluminum as a measure of proton intensities.
The radioactivity of each sample was followed
as long as practical. The results were analyzed by
least-squares techniques using known values of the
half-lives. The final proton-induced cross section
data are the averages of the results from two
